Parliament did not support amendment to release Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian Parliament today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment to the Criminal Code section in which the opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko is condemned.
The amendment would open the doors to the express minister's detention, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce penalties for economic offences in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for the alleged signature of a disadvantageous agreement with Russia for Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not yet firm, the appeal court has the obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that it was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West have arisen doubts about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code with which the former Prime Minister was condemned was supported by 147 members of the vote.
For approval, 226 votes were required.
