IBM History: From the cheese cutter to space flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, with its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was already adopted in 1924 - it was originally a brand used in branches in Canada and South America.
The basis that led to IBM’s birth emerges from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He possessed inventions such as the famous "fix watch", which allows to control the input and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was the businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired his supervisory board.
Flint filed the head of a competition company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him with the company’s management.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM (Watson’s ideas remain the firm basis on which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name indicates, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat cutters and cheese to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson led the company, billing doubled by $9 million and started the company’s large expansion across the continents.
Watson was so crucial for the company that, after almost forty years occupiing the boss’ chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under its direction, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM’s staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and the famous flight to the Moon in 1969).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The "fish" classics, which set up the computer standard of the time, arrived on the market with the name of IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to Chinese company Lenovo, which, for its part, acquired the consulting part of Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began offering full advice and high-value added services.
The strategy IBM has paid over the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, “a smarter planet.”
Its aim is to make a more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned or circumstances have been improved, for example in the transport and administration of cities.
For the trade sector, IBM has not long launched the "Smart Commerce" platform that allows retailers to manage the entire trade cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
In 1932, he opened a branch in then Czechoslovakia, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
