How Travel Prices Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time sold in most cases travel only to the socialist bloc, because travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists were therefore on vacation to the beaches of the DDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, (Sochi in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, the Yugoslav regime then inclined to the west and the Czech tourist journeys were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually not even by the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or to the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the west at the time, but one should be put in the tail with a sleep bag and spend the night all, or have "good known" in the agency.
Still not everything was won.
The so-called "change promise" which was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", which thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of the Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs would acquire. This custom still persist.
The way of travelling the Czechs has suffered an authentic revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was the no longer going to spend the vacation in the DDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which today we are no longer aware of, the fact that to the current favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989, it was not possible to travel freely, because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
In the early 1990s, the exemption of visas to travel to neighboring Western Europe was imposed, causing a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not seem tired of the trips to the west, everyone wanted to see them at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech groups were sleeping in parks in tents, as our income from then did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs at that time was taking food (conserved, embedded, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, buy free Western currency.
Our level of living increased and with it also average wages, which in 1997 resulted in an increase in travel demand.
With the increased travel demand, the agencies began regularly to prepare the trips using charter flight connections, making travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of getting discounts for the passenger volume.
In the late 90s of the last century, the Czechs traveled without visa to almost all developed countries except the US, which simplified our journeys even further.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism occurred already in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Czech to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with tourists from Czech to far and warm countries are departing every year. This winter will already fly directly from Czech to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visit nearly 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. removed visas for Czech tourists, with which our country became among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their abroad holidays (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have been spent on travel abroad more than 15,000 Czech crowns per head, including expenses on the stay site.
