Bartlett’s team found half a million fans from right-wing groups across Europe and then directed ads to them, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey that asked about their educational level, attitudes towards violence and optimism about their own future.
By reaching Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers of 14 extreme-right matches in 11 European countries – all without leaving the office.
“It’s a completely new way of doing an investigation,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, men and angry by immigration.
However, in a sort of turn, “those who combine their activism in line with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind the computer screen.”
DEMOS’ work is just an example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything, from health problems to social trends as expressed in "I like", wall messages and state updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook’s “data-new” is generating an increase in research, boosting the number of academic jobs with the name of the site in the title up to nearly 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, Facebook’s beauty is that it allows you to study people you couldn’t get closer with a folder on the street.
“Before, when you tried to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
“You would have to go through the game, and they would never allow you access,” Bartlett says.
"Facebook removes all that - you're going to them directly."
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address social health problems.
A recent study conducted by Dr. Megan Moreno from the University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues found that college students who talked about their Facebook drinking acts had a significantly greater risk of having problems with the drink than students who remained silent on the topic.
Moreno suggests that student colleagues, such as residential advisors, could control the site and intervene to help a student publish too many state updates with their drinks.
“You can’t treat a problem if you can’t diagnose it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Child’s Center for Health, Behaviour and Development at the Seattle Child Research Institute, Washington Post.
“We have found a way to identify risky children that would otherwise not be diagnosed.”
Facebook is also constantly "pinking" its own population to obtain data.
The site Data Team has prepared statistics on the status of relationship and Valentine’s Day, the expectation of electoral participation in the middle of the 2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using the information that can be accessed - advocates of digital freedom long ago that argue that the site should make available to other large amounts of data for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, like them or not - the sacrifice of being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of kilometers away is allowing the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
