MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Leads Social Security research to discover the gene of obesity in children and youth; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it leads a research to discover the gene of obesity in children and youth, called the protocol "Childhood and Adolescent Obesity Genetics", which will allow you to count on overweight-associated markers.
In a statement, chief of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Hospital of Specialties at the 21st Century National Medical Center, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutriologists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, the population is invited to participate, whether or not, to attend the IMSS participating sports units in the Valley of Mexico, where testing for minors is carried out every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He emphasized that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Mexico Poniente State) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Unit (Mexico Oriental State).
Once the goal of gathering 500 or 600 minors is achieved, the study will continue in the Independence Sports Unit (sur the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (northern the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
When World Diabetes Day was held on 14 November, he stated that the goal is to gather three thousand children and young people aged six to 14, with their parents’ consent and supervision, for the application of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and inherited family history of diseases, with the aim of avoiding risk factors that trigger suffering such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that Saturdays are applied to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure taking, determining glucose, triglyceride, cholesterol, and insulin and genetic levels (it is intended to identify genes that are associated with infant obesity).
Cruz López noted that this research is due to the concern of healthcare professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
“The 1999 and 2006 health surveys pointed out that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed,” the IMSS specialist said.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on that the country’s population differs from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average Mexican has 65 percent American Indian inheritance, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that overall, obesity genetics result in the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, allowing them to detect whether they have some degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark colored folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors deliver it in writing to parents, to whom each of the measurements and lifestyle changes must be made to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic suffering: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, remain most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport rather than walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sugary beverages, carbohydrates (tamals, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics that are analyzed in this protocol.
Asphalt from UNAM would avoid baches
Rafael Herrera, researcher at UNAM’s Faculty of Chemistry, develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent by the floor were served, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 baches every rain season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a complete chemical faculty researcher in UNAM, who said that if the construction process or maintenance of a floor is possible to reduce the proper amount.
In his conference A technological opinion of the baches, dictated within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory at its office develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and at low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that these types of modified asphalts could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, like some cities in the north of the country, to improve their performance and thus the formation of baches.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, ones high molecular weight, called asphaltines, and others low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius has a nearly solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken.
The above means that on the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but is modifying during the day according to the environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warned.
The FQ researcher noted that Mexico City streets are mostly covered by flexible floor, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphaltic folder, composed of small stones baded in asphalt and then compressed.
Each of the stones that constitutes the folder, he pointed out, is baded with asphalt.
By passing vehicles and generating efforts, it allows forces to spread very well on the floor.
If it was a modified asphalt, it would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphaltic folder, abundantly, a last layer called the rolling folder is placed, which is made of a fine stone material, i.e. a sand that also baths in asphalt.
Because it is about the layer that will be in contact with vehicle tyres, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphaltic folder and provide friction on the way.
Being the part of the floor that will receive and spread the efforts, the rolling folder also requires proper thickness and the material from which it is made should be taken care of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphaltic folder.
When the ground is moist, water spreads inside the folder and it is difficult to come out, this causes a blasting of all layers of the floor and therefore the formation of baches.
In the process of formating a bache, he said, the first to wear is the bearing film and only then the asphaltic folder is affected, but damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be addressed to the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Research System also explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of baches and therefore the thickness of each of the floor layers should always be related to the vehicle load and ensure that it is met, to prevent baches from formating frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and allow repair of the baches easily and without using high temperatures.
