Introduction to a budgetary "gold rule" in the Constitution
The Government of Great Democratic/Christian Social Coalition that is in power in Austria has decided on Tuesday to include in the Constitution a "gold rule" budget to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid possible degradation of Austria's sovereign note by the credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself, who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when Austrian public debt reaches 74.6%, a much higher than the maximum limit of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly lower than debts from countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency was reduced to a single level, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay more than 3 billion euros in interest every year,” said Christian Democratic Vice-Chancellor for Foreign Affairs, Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus responded to a request from the Brussels Summit to the member countries of the eurozone last October: in it, Heads of State and Government requested the inclusion, before the end of 2012, of the reduction of public deficit and the recovery of the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or in a law with equivalent value.
The device adopted by the Austrian government approaches the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt that type of "rule".
Before 2017, the structural public deficit should decrease annually by 0.75% of GDP and, starting in 2017, the federal state’s structural public deficit should not exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional states and municipalities should make balanced budgets.
The goal is to reduce public debt by 2020/2021 under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
