Energy policy:
Facts must be more valuable than dogmas.
If there is a topic that cannot be dealt with taking into account short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and the competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate for an electoral meeting to be the time to reflect on such issues and the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it examines the entire economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, the demographic evolution will result in the duplication of electrical demand by 2050, unless a huge portion of the world’s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the increasing deficiency of fossil resources will have to be reduced to continue producing electricity continuously, without forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains alone in its decision to renounce nuclear energy.
That is not the case of Belgium, which submits its support to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, nor of Switzerland, which aims to only build state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, by citing some examples, continue with determination with their projects.
The United States, after Fukushima, decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of an interrupted plant after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energy, is sometimes presented as an example, reality is against such a speech.
The election of Berlin will suggest an increase in the price of electricity, an increased energy dependence due to the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions due to the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticed.
It should be discussed about the case of Denmark.
European champion in the wind sector, from which he gets 30% of his electricity, is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the wind intermittentness; for this reason his CO2 emissions and the price of his electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbors pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would lead to a strong rise in the price of electricity, leaving realism to the wonderful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of the French refuse to pay and, in fact, do not demonstrate a principle of opposition to that type of energy, according to the surveys.
Let’s remember that our country’s energy policy has lost building an industrial sector with 125,000 director jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it covers a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets that can create non-localized jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would be the sacrifice of much of those SMEs and the loss of 6 billion euros annually in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to work for sixty years when its manufacturer’s collapse is planned?
In order to solve the equation of nuclear energy, we must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no devil source.
Areva’s development of low-CO2, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises strict and transparent control of both existing plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with security.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, the Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operational conditions; it did not cause any consequences either for people or for the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two unprecedented natural disasters, which led to the death of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to these progress and cooperation between the security authorities, and French and German operators and builders, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While all electrical actors who want to build a plant study it, the interruption of their construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for Areva and EDF competitors, as it would leave them free way to assume leadership in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is indispensable and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogmas and partisan manoeuvres dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy applied by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the figure policy, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France’s “human rights country”.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students who has jumped on the headlines, with the Minister of Interior (see Libération newspaper of May 23) proclaiming from the past that France "doesn't need foreign talents, workers or counterparts."
However, it is rarely analyzed from the economic point of view.
The question is that there is a lot of consensus between the left and the right on this issue.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the guidance by declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country with nearly two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone said Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take care of the entire poverty of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared fear of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish fountainers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered to be a burden for French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity with which they act with regard to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande is limited to include banalities, indicating that the code-development will allow to solve the "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, perhaps is profitable electorally, but economically is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work that summarizes the most recent knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among jobs specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and countries.
The limitation of immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace domestic workers, particularly those under-qualified, by pressing to reduce their wages.
But experience shows that immigrants are in fact rather complementary than replacements for domestic workers and mainly exercise professions in lack of employment sectors.
Poorly qualified immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most qualified in dynamic sectors where training does not meet staff demand.
A positive effect on wages
Similarly as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country with lack of anesthetics, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of nationals to have a positive impact on the wages and employment of nationals.
Taking into account the above, Giovanni Peri estimated that an increase of 1% in migration flows represents an increase in long-term real wages from 0.6 to 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity contributed by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel prizes and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they contribute an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will make a net contribution of EUR 150,000 to average public budgets throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go to search for the growth points missing him "with his teeth."
These teeth, which dissuaded immigrants, had exactly the reverse effect.
