The Nord Stream, new gateway of Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly communicates Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with a large pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the banks of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, at the opening of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline that directly communicates, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolicly, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, have together rotated the steering wheel of the valve controlling Russian gas entry into the Western Europe network.
With this new pipeline, additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will reach Western Europe each year through a first had 1,224 km communicating the St. Petersburg region with the Mecklenburg-Pomerania Land.
A second tube should be concluded in late 2012 that will allow a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas to be supplied, i.e. enough to cover all French consumption.
Furthermore, we already talk about the possibility of building a third tube on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work presents victory airs.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will enable the supply of gas directly to Germany, avoiding land traffic through third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be harder to influence Russia threatening it to close access to Western Europe’s markets.
At the highlight of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically delicate.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has obtained increased supply safety.
But the price is a weakening of energy Europe, since the project has generated a gap between eastern and western Europeans.
Russia has known, in just five years, to triumph its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
“This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that binds us organically,” François Fillon confirmed during the inauguration of the gas pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the large contracts in the gas sector are as political as economical.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of the managers of Gazprom, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of gas arrival.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it from vessel anchors.
It is supported on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m depth.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mine fields dating back to World War II.
"It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them, for caution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to extremize the protection measures of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs as 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted throughout its length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Sweden’s waters, but the project officials resigned from it when they saw that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to permanently establish itself in the sea off their coasts.
"In the event of a failure, we'll interrupt gas passage in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In the event of leakage, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But constructors consider unlikely a leakage, since they have predicted joints that, according to the forecasts, will have a leakage every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the gas pipeline is guaranteed by a submarine robot, dragged by a vessel, conducting outer inspections, as well as by a device circulating through the inside of the gas pipeline.
With the shape of a pure, it is introduced into the interior of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without any type of repair.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined their strengths to be able to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of shares.
To her, the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a common company called Nord Stream, responsible for building and exploiting the gas pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zoug, Switzerland, where the taxation is especially favorable.
Then, Gazprom rented the company, for a period of twenty-five renewable years, all the gas transport capabilities.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported,” said Jens Müller.
The funding for the construction of the gas pipeline has been made by 30% with shareholders’ contribution and by 70% with bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach €7.4 billion for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom alone takes the risk of expenditure.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sand coast planted with pine pine.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas upon arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
Total capacity will be three million an hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand book.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to return the taste of writing to people.
It has an adventure air, from hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine booklet is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine books with the current appearance were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design notebook, but distinguished, on the market.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant of the company, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The booklet is inspired by an ancient production technique, soft skin (top skin), which refers to a barned cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the banks.
This type of book was highly appreciated by writers and travellers.
“Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Modo Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first years has been left away, in which only 3,000 books were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer’s profile, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open spirit and cult.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers at its beginning, now owns about 100 and has two offices since 2008: one in Milan and the other in New York.
Distribute his bookbooks in libraries, from the Fnac to the small shops in the center of the cities, and he has been able to impose his identity.
“We have adapted to times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists expose their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard caps, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: pockets, agendas, pens, computer covers... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that causes envy: in the fall of 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the SG Capital Europe investment fund, currently Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in Moleskine’s history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for jobs.
The 15th Week for the Employment of Disabilities begins today.
Despite a resolved public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among persons with disabilities doubles the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the entire population.
Discouraging?
“No,” says Éric Blanchet, Director-General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabilities.
“The progress made for fifteen years is considerable.
At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still a lot to do."
It should be noted that unemployed people continue to face numerous obstacles to access employment.
They usually have an older age: 37% are over 50 years old (average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished the bachelor’s degree, and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for disabled, compared to an average of 38%.
That is, there are numerous issues that particularly difficult the return to the labour world and that "constitute the quid of the problem," says Christian Grapin, Director-General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
Furthermore, there are those that are not mentioned; people’s mentality advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre for the Cité association pointed out that the directors surveyed have “a level of knowledge about low disability,” with an “overrepresentation of people on wheelchair, physical or intellectual disabled”.
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a goal that was set on a... 1987 law.
According to the latest available figures, dating from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
"We now reach about 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the agency responsible for raising contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The test: the number of establishments "submitted to this contribution", as well as the amounts paid, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated high pressure for businesses,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects true awareness, particularly among the big groups.”
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies possessing between 20 and 49 employees have disabled employees in their employment, compared to 82% of companies of between 100 and 199 employees.
